│ <2 x i32> poison, i32 %0, i32 0\n  %3 = shufflevector <2 x i32> %5, <2 x    │
│ i32> poison, <2 x i32> zeroinitializer\n\nThis indicates that the SLP       │
│ vectorizer is creating an insertelement instruction that doesn't dominate   │
│ its use in a shufflevector instruction. The issue occurs when the           │
│ vectorizer tries to build a vector from scalar values using insertelement   │
│ instructions starting with poison, but the insertion point for these        │
│ instructions is not properly set to dominate all their uses.\n\n2.          │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows that the Scalar Evolution Analysis     │
│ runs first, then the SLP vectorizer attempts to transform the IR. The crash │
│ occurs during verification, indicating that the SLP vectorizer created      │
│ invalid IR where an instruction doesn't dominate its uses. This typically   │
│ happens when instructions are inserted at incorrect locations in the        │
│ CFG.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: Looking at the gather function in           │
│ SLPVectorizer.cpp (around line 14994), we see that it creates a poison      │
│ vector as the starting point: `Value *Vec = PoisonValue::get(VecTy);`. Then │
│ it uses `CreateInsertElement` to build up the vector by inserting elements. │
│ However, the IRBuilder's insertion point may not be set correctly when      │
│ dealing with complex control flow involving PHIs and multiple basic blocks. │
│ The issue is that the initial poison vector creation doesn't account for    │
│ proper dominance when the vectorized code spans multiple basic blocks with  │
│ PHIs.\n\nThe problem is specifically in the `gather` function where         │
│ `PoisonValue::get(VecTy)` is used to create the initial vector. This        │
│ creates a constant value that doesn't have a proper instruction placement   │
│ in the CFG, leading to dominance issues when subsequent instructions        │
│ reference it in different basic blocks.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n+    │
│ The fix should ensure that when creating the initial vector in the gather   │
│ function, we use an instruction that is properly placed in the CFG to       │
│ dominate all its uses. Instead of using `PoisonValue::get(VecTy)` which     │
│ creates a constant, we should create a proper poison instruction at the     │
│ correct insertion point.\n\n5. Conclusion: The issue is that the SLP        │
│ vectorizer creates a poison constant value that doesn't have proper         │
│ dominance properties in complex CFGs with PHIs. The fix is to replace the   │
│ constant poison value creation with a proper instruction that is inserted   │
│ at a location that dominates all its uses. This will ensure the generated   │
│ IR is valid and passes the verifier."})                                     │
